data_answer:
% of licensed 16 year olds that get into accidents: 624,000/1,634,000 x 100 = 38.188 %

 

% of licensed 17 year olds that get into accidents: 680,000/2,209,000 x 100 = 30.783 %

% of licensed 19 year olds that get into accidents: 670,000/2,653,000 x 100 = 25.254 %

 

25.254% < 28.380% < 30.783% < 38.188% 

 

I would have to disagree with Jose's position on this topic because the amount of accidents per age group is significantly higher for 16 years old than 19 year olds. data_answer:
While it is true that, according to the table, 16-year-olds have the fewest number of accidents (624,000), I disagree with Jose because he has misinterpreted the statistics. 16-year-olds have the fewest number of accidents if one doesn't account for the fact that they have the least amount of licensed drivers. Jose's claim can be refuted by simply finding the percentage of accidents to number of licensed drivers.

16-year-olds:
(624,000 / 1,634,000) x 100 = 38.19% 

 

17-year-olds:
(680,000 / 2,209,000) x 100 = 30.78% 

 

18-year-olds:
(720,000 / 2,537,000) x 100 = 28.38%

19-year-olds: 
(670,000 / 2,653,000) x 100 = 25.25% 

As demonstrated, the 16-year-old accident rate of 38.19% is far greater than the other three age groups.

Although Jose--clearly through "analyzing" the table above--feels that 16-year-olds are the safest teen drivers, I would have to disagree with him. He fails to realize that, firstly, the 16-year-old group has also the leasy number of licensed drivers. The reason it is the group with the lowest number of accidents is because it does not have many drivers to get into these accidents to begin with. As a result, it is necessary to compute how many accidents happen per licensed16-year-old on average instead of solely focusing in on the number of accidents. 

       There are 624,000 accidents amongst 16-year-old drivers, who number in 1,634,000. If we take the number of accidents and divide it by the number of drivers, we get about 0.38 accidents per unit. Let's compare this with the average accidents per driver of other groups--17-year olds have 0.30 accidents per unit, 18-year-olds have 0.28, and 19-year-olds have 0.25. These values are all less than that of the16-year-old group, which makes 16-year-olds the likeliest group to gent into accidents. 

       My case can also be bolstered by Table 2, which shows that 16-year-olds have a 24% chance of getting into accidents, while 17-year-olds only have a 16% chance. This, in sum, shows that 16-year-olds actually have one of the greatest risks for accidents and are actually the least safe teenage drivers.

I was terrified, it looked like a human with big wings, almost like an angel, I followed the shadow and hear a thud and then smoke come up from the ground. I rush tpwards it curious and wanting some answers. When I approach it quivers away from me, and I stop slowly reaching out my hand so he knows I'm not dangerous.

"I'm not a dog" The human like creature says bluntly.

He's handsome, he's Korean but he has white blond hair and long beating wings protruding from his back, the handsome man looks at his wings and tucks them in so there pressed up tightly to his back.

"Here, take my shirt" I say pulling it off over my head and handing it to him.

He gladly take it and puts it on over his head.

"I'm Kim Kibum, but just call me Key" he says standing up slowly.

He's taller than me and really skinny, he's really cute.

"I'm Kim Jonghyun, but please call me Jonghyun" I say with a charming smile. "Let's go to my place and get you bandaged up"

Key smiles and nods, we head off in the direction of my house the lights are off and it's quiet, I go up to the door and unlock it and walking in and waiting for Key to follow.

"How come you haven't asked about my wings?" He asks quietly.

"Because if you want to tell me then you can, but I won't push you" I say with a smile and turn on the lights.

My house looks rustic the colors are made up of autumn reds. And it's calming like it's in the country side, which we pretty much are since there isn't another house for miles. It smelled of cinnamon from the candle I had lit before I went out.

"Make yourself at home" I say and head to the bathroom for the first Aid kit.

When I go back downstairs Key is passed out on the couch and I smile warmly and grab a blanket and carefully cover him with it so he doesn't freeze. Then I head upstairs and start getting ready for bed, when I finally do I lay down and within minutes I am passed out.

 

When I wake up I smell food cooking then I jolt up completly forgetting about Key I throw on some pants and head downstairs and into the kitchen he's wearing a pair of my pants and my T-shirt he looks at me and smiles, I can see the slight outline of his wings then I look at the stove he's making pancakes and bacon.

"Good morning" he says with a smile

"Morning" I say smiling back.

"I hope you don't mind me cooking, cooking is one of my favorite things to do"

"No, not at all, I could get use to this."

Key smiles at me and I smile back and sit down at the table and watch his back as he cooks. I want to know about his wings but I don't want to ask, will I ever find out? I question but shake my head and look at the plate he brings over to me and I lick my lips.
